posts.name: Devin Slattery
posts.cooked: We custom machine our own 2 speed swerves and this year we had inefficiencies as high as 74% of free speed. For example, our high gear was 21.7 ft/s and we plateaued at 16ft/s. I was curious what commercial swerves or other custom swerves inefficiencies are/what ft/s you actually achieve vs what you’re free speed is.

posts.name: John Fogarty
posts.cooked:
What motors were you using?

With speed control properly tuned we could hit nearly the max theoretical speed  advertised by our SDS modules.

Robot weight, traction, thermal conditions of the motor, and battery state of charge, and more… effect the ability to hit the max speed.

posts.name: Brendan Simons, 5406
posts.cooked:
Try out some of the drivetrain simators linked below.   A robot’s top speed is not determined by gearing only, despite how some teams describe it.  The motors you use, the current limits you set, the sprint distance, and yes " inefficiencies" all conspire to prevent you from reaching your “top speed”.  I would wager that very few robots reached 21 fps on the field.

ReCalc - a collaboration focused mechanical design calculator.

https://ambcalc.com/drivetrain

ILITE Drivetrain Simulator, v2020 General Forum

posts.name: Devin Slattery
posts.cooked: We are using Falcon 500’s. We weighted 125 but we plateaued at 16ft/s with a new fully charged battery going in a straight line.

Devin:

straight line.

For how long? Motors are worse at generating torque at high speeds so your acceleration will approach 0 as you reach your free speed. Like it takes about as longer to go from 16 to 17ft/s than it will to go from 0 to 16 ft/s. For robots geared super high, you might just not have enough space to reach free speed in the length of an FRC field.

posts.name: Devin Slattery
posts.cooked: Almost the whole length of an FRC field.

posts.name: Emerson OHara
posts.cooked:
Are you still accelerating towards the end or do you plateau pretty early? We were able to hit pretty close to ~16.4ft/s (5.0m/s) geared for 18.2ft/s with Krakens (no FOC ) on the beta Thrifty Swerve v2. Robot right now is 123lbs. At gearing close to 22ft/s I think you’d be low down on the motor curve enough to still have plenty of torque. What are you supply and stator current limits? We are running 120 stator / 60 supply fwiw.

I’d log motor current and see how much you are using, it’s also possible you’re pulling enough current that the voltage is dropping and not recovering enough effectively capping your speed ( IE at full speed, robot voltage is sub 11v).
